-- ── Found ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Found is a fintech platform offering business banking built for the self-employed, combining a checking account with automated bookkeeping, real-time tax estimates, invoicing, contractor payments, and an AI-powered assistant.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium (free core account with optional paid tiers)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (paid tiers from $35/month)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2019, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$51-200 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Found Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Found review 2026: business banking pricing, tax tools, invoicing, and AI assistant for the self-employed. Compare Found to Novo, Lili, and Bluevine.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Found is a fintech company that provides business banking designed specifically for freelancers, gig workers, sole proprietors, and other self-employed business owners, pairing a business checking account with built-in bookkeeping, expense tracking, invoicing, and tax tools so that customers need fewer separate pieces of software to run their finances. The company was founded in 2019 by two former Square executives, CEO Lauren Myrick, an accountant who spent eight years at Square, and CIO Connor Dunn, a software engineer who spent five years there. Found publicly launched and raised a $12.75 million seed round led by Sequoia Capital in May 2021, and has since raised additional capital from investors including Founders Fund and Lightspeed Venture Partners, bringing its total funding to roughly $124 million at a reported valuation of around $406 million. The company is a financial technology provider rather than a chartered bank; its underlying deposit and card-issuing services have been provided through FDIC-insured banking partners, with public sources referencing both Piermont Bank and Lead Bank as partner banks over the company's history, and customer funds are FDIC-insured up to $250,000 per depositor per ownership category through those partnerships.

Found's core product is built around eliminating the disconnect between a business's banking activity and its bookkeeping and tax obligations, a gap that traditionally required self-employed workers to pay for a separate accounting or invoicing tool on top of a bank account. Every transaction that flows through a Found account is automatically categorized for bookkeeping purposes, and the platform calculates real-time estimated tax liability as money comes in, letting users see, transaction by transaction, roughly how much they should set aside for quarterly estimated taxes rather than discovering a large bill at tax season. Found also supports unlimited invoicing directly from the account, letting users bill clients and track payment status without a separate invoicing subscription, and it handles contractor payments end-to-end, including W-9 collection and 1099-NEC filing, without charging a fee per contractor, a workflow that would otherwise require a payroll or contractor-management platform. Found's account structure includes up to ten 'Pockets,' sub-accounts that let users automatically set aside money for specific purposes such as taxes, payroll, or savings goals, functioning similarly to the envelope-budgeting approach offered by some consumer banking apps but applied to business cash flow.

A more recent addition to the platform is Found Assistant, an AI-powered feature built into the Found account that can answer questions about a user's finances, help complete tasks such as moving money or sending invoices, and provide account support around the clock, with money-movement actions requiring explicit user approval before execution. This positions Found as one of a wave of fintech products embedding conversational AI directly into everyday financial workflows rather than treating it as a separate chatbot layered on top of a support center.

Found's pricing follows a freemium structure with three tiers. The base Found plan is free, with no monthly fee, and includes business checking, debit cards, team cards, up to ten Pockets, expense tracking, tax estimates, contractor payments, and unlimited invoicing, making the core banking and bookkeeping functionality available at no cost. Found Plus costs $35 per month, or $315 per year when paid annually (a 25 percent discount versus monthly billing), and adds 1.50 percent APY on balances up to $20,000, the ability to import external transactions for more complete bookkeeping, unlimited custom auto-categorization rules and tags, and priority phone support, aimed at growing businesses that want more automation around their books. Found Pro costs $80 per month, or $720 per year annually (also a 25 percent annual discount), and adds 2.50 percent APY on all balances with no cap, 1 percent cash back on purchases, a dedicated account manager, a premium metal debit card, free check sending, and discounted wire transfers at $10 instead of $15. Both paid tiers include a 30-day free trial.

Found's revenue has grown substantially, reaching $20.2 million in 2025, up from $13.9 million in 2024, reflecting continued adoption among its target market. The company's target audience is explicitly the self-employed: independent contractors, freelancers, creators, and small solo or micro-business owners who need business banking but do not want to purchase and reconcile data across several separate tools for bookkeeping, invoicing, and tax preparation. This puts Found in direct competition with a cluster of neobanks targeting similar customers, including Novo, which is known for fee-free checking, built-in invoicing, and integrations with tools like Shopify and QuickBooks but offers no interest on deposits; Lili, which started as a freelancer-focused app and has grown into a broader small-business platform with strong savings APY and comprehensive live customer support; Bluevine, which combines checking, lending, and higher FDIC coverage up to $3 million with competitive APY; and Mercury, which targets a more startup-oriented customer base. Found differentiates itself primarily through the depth of its built-in tax-estimation and contractor-payment tooling, which is more purpose-built for solo self-employed workflows than the more general small-business feature sets of some competitors, and through its early embrace of an AI assistant integrated directly into the banking product. Its main tradeoffs relative to competitors are that its customer support is described as leaning more heavily on email and self-service tools compared to phone- or chat-first rivals like Lili, and that top-tier interest rates and cash back require paying for the Pro subscription rather than being available on the free account.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '22c9265b-8d90-4eb5-973c-a18df96a2516';

